# .ignore — фильтр для qex (read by Rust `ignore` crate, same as ripgrep).
#
# Important: NOT the same as .gitignore.
# - .gitignore — what gets committed to git.
# - .ignore     — what gets into the qex semantic index.
# Both files are read independently and may overlap — that's fine.
#
# ============================================================================
# HOW TO ADAPT TO YOUR PROJECT
# ============================================================================
# 1. Copy this file to the project root as `.ignore` (with the leading dot).
# 2. Edit the WHITELIST block below to keep only directories where active
#    development happens. Everything else is excluded automatically.
# 3. After edits — reindex:
#      mcp__qex__clear_index(path=<project-root>)
#      mcp__qex__index_codebase(path=<project-root>, force=true)
#    Without clear_index, stale files remain indexed.
#
# ============================================================================
# WHY WHITELIST, NOT BLACKLIST
# ============================================================================
# Less noise in the index → cleaner BM25 ranking → fewer false hits in top-5.
# Bonus: a new scratch folder added tomorrow is auto-excluded; you don't have
# to keep editing this file.
#
# ============================================================================
# DEFAULT EXAMPLE — standard src-layout Python project
# ============================================================================

# Root: exclude everything…
/*

# …except active development directories (EDIT for your project)
!/src/
!/tests/
!/scripts/
!/docs/
!/plans/
!/.claude/

# ============================================================================
# Alternative example — project with multiple prototypes / vendored deps
# ============================================================================
# /*
# !/main_app/
# !/legacy_prototype/
# !/shared_lib/
#
# Inside an active directory you can do a second-level whitelist:
# main_app/*
# !main_app/core/
# !main_app/api/
# !main_app/tests/

# ============================================================================
# Hidden directories (.claude/, .cursor/, ...)
# ============================================================================
# Rust `ignore` crate filters hidden files by default (like ripgrep without
# --hidden). Even `!/.claude/` may not work because the hidden-file filter is
# a separate layer from gitignore rules. If you need to index a hidden folder
# and it's not picked up — consider moving content under a non-hidden path,
# or run qex with an explicit include override.
